ed","1346":"1346","1378":"1378","1376":"1376","1384":"1384","1372":"1372","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","1380":"1380","Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England","linco":"Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Anderson","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish and northern English: patronymic from the personal name <i>Ander(s)</i>, a northern Middle English form of   Andrew  , + <i>son</i> ‘son’. The frequency of the surname in Scotland is attributable, at least in part, to the fact that Saint Andrew is the patron saint of Scotland, so the personal name has long enjoyed great popularity there. Legend has it that the saint's relics were taken to Scotland in the 4th century by a certain Saint Regulus. In North America, this surname has absorbed many cognate or like-sounding surnames in other languages, notably Scandinavian (see 3 and 4 below), but also Ukrainian <b>Andreychenko</b> etc.","German: patronymic from the personal name   Anders  , hence a cognate of 1 above.","Americanized form (and a less common Swedish variant) of Swedish   Andersson  , a cognate of 1 above."],"variants":[{"name":"Andrew","meanings":["English and Scottish: from the usual vernacular English form (recorded from the 13th century onward) of the New Testament Greek personal name   Andreas  . In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed many cognates from other languages, e.g. Czech <b>Ondřej</b> (see   Ondrey  ) and Albanian   Ndreu  , and also their patronymics and other derivatives (see examples at   Andrews  ).","History: The surname Andrew was first brought to North America from England by Robert Andrew (died 1668), who settled in Boxford, MA."]}]},{"name":"Duncan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Anglicized form of the Gaelic name Donnchadh , also used among people without Scottish connections. This was the name of a 7th-century Scottish saint (abbot of Iona) and two medieval kings of Scotland. The final ‐<i>n</i> in the Anglicized form seems to be the result of confusion with the Gaelic word <i>ceann</i> ‘head’ in the Latinized form <i>Duncanus</i>.  Compare Irish  Donagh ."],"variants":[{"name":"Donnchadh","meanings":["Gaelic: compound of Old Celtic <i>donn</i> ‘brown’ + <i>chadh</i> ‘chief’ or ‘noble’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Duncan Anderson was born in 1346, in Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom. He had at least 3 sons and 3 daughters with Katherine de Roet. He died in 1384, in his hometown, at the age of 38."},"et":{"1346–1384":"1346–1384","1346–Female":"1346–Surnud","1370–Male":"1370–Surnud","1372–Female":"1372–Surnud","1376–Male":"1376–Surnud","1378–Female":"1378–Surnud","1380–Male":"1380–Surnud","1382–Female":"1382–Surnud","1346":"1346","1378":"1378","1376":"1376","1384":"1384","1372":"1372","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","1380":"1380","Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England","linco":"Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1346–1384":"1346–1384","1346–Female":"1346–Kuollut","1370–Male":"1370–Kuollut","1372–Female":"1372–Kuollut","1376–Male":"1376–Kuollut","1378–Female":"1378–Kuollut","1380–Male":"1380–Kuollut","1382–Female":"1382–Kuollut","1346":"1346","1378":"1378","1376":"1376","1384":"1384","1372":"1372","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","1380":"1380","Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Lincolnshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England","linco":"Lincolnshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1346–1384":"1346–1384","1346–Female":"1346–Décédée","1370–Male":"1370–Décédé","1372–Female":"1372–Décédée","1376–Male":"1376–Décédé","1378–Female":"1378–Décédée","1380–Male":"1380–Décédé","1382–Female":"1382–Décédée",